SATIRE XIV.

ARGUMENT.

The subjects of this Satire are of the most important kind, and the poet, as if fully aware of it, has treated them in his best manner. In none of his works does he take a loftier flight3 in none is he more vigorous and energetic3 in none more clear and precise in his style, more original in his conceptions, more happy iu his illustrations, or more powerful and commanding m his general deductions.

The whole is directed to the one great end of self- improvement. By showing the dreadful facility with which children copy the vices of their parents, lff; 31 ff; he points out the neces sity, as well as the sacred duty, of giving them examples of domestic purity and virtue. 38. .85.
